USE OF A TIGHTER FITTING SPILL BLOCKING GATE PIECE AT REAR OF VAN SHOULD PREVENT ANY FURTHER INCIDENTS OF THIS TYPE.

column168: TRUCK AND TRAILER, FULLY LOADED WITH GASOLINE WAS TRAVELING WEST ON HWY 50 IN SACRAMENTO WHEN AN OUT OF CONTROL AUTOMOBILE CROSSED IN FRONT OF TRUCK. LEFT FRONT FENDER OF TRUCK HIT LEFT REAR FENDER OF AUTOMOBILE.  DRIVER BRAKED HARD.  TRUCK AND TRAILER SWUNG 180 DEGREES, AS TRAILER ROLLED 3 TIMES.  SOME GASOLINE ESCAPED AND A FIRE SARTED.  FIREMAN ALLOWED ALL GASOLINE TO BURN TO AVOID POSSIBLE ENVIRONMENTAL PROBLEMS.  DRIVER OF TRUCK WAS NOT INJURED.  DRIVER OF AUTO WENT BY AMBULANCE TO HOSPITAL WITH MINOR INJURIES.  APPROXIMATELY 6 WITNESSES AND HP OFFICERS ALL AGREE THAT AUTO DRIVER WAS CLEARLY AT FAULT AND THE TRUCK DRIVER ACTED PROPERLY.  THE EXACT CAUSE OF GASOLINE LEAKAGE AND FIRE IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION BY C.H.P AND D.O.T.

column42: COMPOUND, CLEANING, LIQUID (CONTAINING PHOSPHORIC ACID, ACETIC ACID, SODIUM HYDROXIDE OR POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE)
column168: ON SEPTEMBER 11, 1995, RIEDEL/SMITH WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND TO A LEAKING TRAILER AT THE COORS BREWERY IN GOLDEN, CO.  UPON ARRIVAL AT APPROXIMATELY 12:45 PM, THE RIEDEL CREW DISCOVERED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID (8 TO 12 OUNCES) HAD LEAKED FROM THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE CONCRETE FLOOR AT THE COORS RECEIVING DOCK.  THE AREA IMPACTED BY THE LEAK WAS LESS THAN ONE CONCRETE FLOOR AT THE COORS RECEIVING DOCK.  THE AREA IMPACTED BY THE LEAK WAS LESS THAN ONE SQUARE FOOT, AND DID NOT INVOLVE ANY WATERWAYS, OR ACCESS TO A WATERWAY VIA THE SEWER SYSTEM.  THE RIEDEL CREW DETERMINED THAT THE LIQUID WAS A SODIUM HYDROXIDE BASED METAL CLEANER, AND IMMEDIATELY NEUTRALIZED THE LIQUID WITH CRITIC ACID.  INSIDE THE TRAILER WERE SIXTY DRUMS OF THE CLEANER (DCT CR-23-66).  THE RIEDEL CREW INSPECTED THE DRUMS AND DISCOVERED THAT EVERY ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD LOOSE BUNGS. EACH BUNG WAS ONE AND ONE-HALF TO TWO DRUMS FROM BEING TIGHT ENOUGH TO SEAT THE GASKET WHICH SEALS THE DRUM.  AS A RESULT, NEARLY EVERY DRUM HAD DCT-CR-23-66 ON THE TOP DRUM DUE TO JOSTLING DURING TRANSPORTATION AND EXPANSION DUE TO THE CHANGE IN ALTITUDE FROM MICHIGAN TO COLORADO.  THE SOURCE OF MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER FLOOR WHICH LED TO THE EXTERNAL LEAK WAS A GROUP OF FOUR DRUMS AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER WHICH HAD PARTIALLY SHIFTED OFF OF THEIR PALLET.  BY BEING PARTIALLY OFF THEIR PALLET, THESE DRUMS WERE RESTING AT ANY ANGLE WHICH ALLOWED THE DCT-CR-23-66 TO RUN OFF THE TOP OF THE DRUM AND ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  ONCE THE SITUATION INSIDE THE TRAILER WAS ASSESSED, CLEANUP OF THE DRUMS AND TRAILER BEGAN. THE RIEDEL CREW SPREAD CITRIC ACID ON THE TOPS OF THE DRUMS TO NEUTRALIZE THE LEAKING MATERILA.  THE BUNGS ON EACH DRUM WERE THAN TIGHTENED AND THE PALLETS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER USING A FORKLIFT PROVIDED BY COORS.  THE DRUMS WHICH HAD SHIFTED OFF OF THEIR PALLETS WERE PLACED BACK ON PALLETS AND REMOVED AS WELL.  ONCE THE TRAILER WAS EMPTY, THE APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF GALLON OF DCT-CR-23-66 WHICH WAS ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH CRITIC ACID.  WATER AND RAGS WERE THEN USED TO MOP UP THE MATERIAL FROM THE FLOOR UNTIL THE RESIDUE WAS REMOVED.  THE UNDERSIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED IN A SIMILAR MANNER AS WELL AS THE IMPACTED CONCRETE.  IT IS POSSIBLE THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF DCT-CR-23-66 REMAINED WITHIN THE CRACKS BETWEEN THE TRAILER FLOOR AND ITS UNDERSIDE WHICH ARE INACCESSIBLE WITHOUT DISMANTLEMENT OF THE TRAILER.  INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER TO ASSESS CORROSION RELATED TO THIS INCIDENT IS RECOMMENDED.  ALL SIXTY DRUMS WERE CLEANED AFTER NEUTRALIZATION USING RAGS AND WATER.  THE DRUMS WERE CLOSELY CHECKED FOR DAMAGE AND NONE WAS DETECTED.  AFTER CLEANING, THE COORS REPRESENTATIVE INSPECTED THE DRUMS AND ACCEPTED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT.  THE DRIVER INSPECTED THE TRAILER AND RELEASED THE RIEDEL CREW AT APPROXIMATELY 3:30 P.M.  IF YOU HAVE ANY FURTHER QUESTION REGARDING THIS RESPONSE PLEASE CONTACT ME AT (303) 373-4400. column168: CAMPBELL OIL COMPANY TRUCK WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON ST. RT. 83 NORTH WOOSTER, OHIO LOADED WITH 8500 GALLONS OF GASOLINE IN ROUTE TO ONE OF OUR CITO LOCATIONS LOCATED IN BURBANK, OHIO.  WEATHER CONDITIONS WERE SUNNY AND CLEAR.  THE DRIVER STATED HE GLANCED DOWN TO HIS FEET AND WHEN HE LOOKED UP THE TRUCK RAN OFF THE LIGHT SHOULDER OF THE ROAD AND LANDED SIDEWAYS IN THE DITCH.  THE DRIVER WAS NOT INJURED AND CLIMBED OUT OF THE DOOR.  TOTAL GALLONS OF GASOLINE LOST WAS 57 GALLONS.  THE OHIO STATE PATROL NOTIFIED OUR OFFICE THAT THERE HAD BEEN AN ACCIDENT.  WE THEN CALLED OUR 24-HOUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TELEPHONE NUMBER AND SET FORTH OUR OIL SPILL AND INCIDENT RESPONSE PLAN.  VARIOUS ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL AND CLEAN-UP CREWS WERE ABLE TO SECURE THE SCENE AND TRANSFER PRODUCT INTO ANOTHER TRUCK.  THIS WAS A CASE OF OF LACK OF CONCENTRATION BY ONE OF OUR DRIVERS.  A POST-ACCIDENT MEETING WAS HELD WITH THE DRIVER AND DISCIPLINARY ACTION WAS TAKEN.  MORE DISCUSSIONS ARE BEING HELD BY OUR COMPANY TO BETTER UNDERSTAND WHAT WE CAN DO TO PREVENT ACCIDENTS IN THE FUTURE INCLUDING DRIVER AWARENESS.

column168: SWITCH CREW WAS SWITCHING CARS TO BE SPOTTED IN MORTON INTERNATIONAL.  A COUPLING WAS MADE ON GAPX 9075.  THE PRESSURE DISK WAS RUPTURED DUE TO OVER PRESSURIZING WHILE LOADING.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON WAS SPLASHED OUT.  SOME OF THE CHEMICAL SPLASHED ON A BRAKEMAN MAKING THE COUPLING. THE BRAKEMAN FLUSHED HIMSELF WITH WATER AND WAS TAKEN TO THE DOCTOR.  THE DOCTOR STATE HE WAS OK BUT TO CONTINUE TO FLUSH WITH WATER AND COME BACK ON THE 11TH WHICH WAS MONDAY.  THE BRAKEMAN WAS BACK ON MONDAY AND WAS RELEASED WITH NO TIME LOST.  IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE INCIDENT MORTON INTERNATIONAL WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY RESPONDED WITHIN 10 MIN.  SINCE THEY WERE ONLY 100 YARDS AWAY.  MORTON INTERNATIONAL REPLACED THE RUPTURED DISK AND STATED THE CAUSE WAS OVER PRESSURIZING WHILE LOADING.  THERE WAS SUCH AN INSIGNIFICANT AMOUNT SPLASHED THAT NONE COULD BE DETECTED ON THE TRACK BALLAST.

THE INVOLVED SHIPMENT (1 SKID) WAS CRUSHED WHEN RECEIVED AT THE INDIANAPOLIS TERMINAL DUE TO THE STACKING OF A HEAVIER SKID (1,000 LBS.) ON TOP OF THIS SHIPMENT.  THE WEIGHT OF THIS SKID CAUSED ONE BOARD ON THE SKID TO BREAK, THUS CAUSING ONE CARTON OF THE INVOLVED SHIPMENT TO SINK PARTIALLY BELOW THE SKID.  THE TOWMOTOR OPERATOR WASN'T AWARE OF THIS, AND CONSEQUENTLY WHEN HE PUT HIS TOWMOTOR BLADES UNDER THE SKID TO REMOVE IT FROM THE TRAILER, HE PUNCTURED THE CARTON, CAUSING THE BAG TO LEAK.  AT THIS TIME OCCURENCE, NO SKIDS THAT ARE HEAVIER THAN THE BOTTOM SKID SHOULD STACKED UPON EACH OTHER.  THE LEAKING BAG AND 1 OTHER CARTON AND ITS CONTENTS WERE PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM. column168: A RANDOLPHS DRIVER WAS TRANSFERRING FUEL FROM HIS CARGO TANK, INTO A STORAGE TANK. WHILE DOING PAPERWORK INSIDE HIS TRUCK, THE STORAGE TANK OVERRAN. MULUNIX CORP WAS CALLED TO HANDLE THE CLEANUP PROCEDURE, AND IMMEDIATELY, THEY DISPTACHED A TRUCK LOAD OF LIME TO THE SCENE TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT.  SOME OF THE FUEL WAS CAUGHT WITHIN THE STORAGE TANK'S CONTAINMENT AND IT WAS PUMPED OUT AND DISPOSED OF.  THE REST OF THE FUEL SPILLED ONTO A GRAVEL PARKING LOT, AND WAS LATER EXCAVATED.  DNR OFFICALAS WERE MADE AWARE OF THE SPILL, AND AGREED TO THE CLEANUP PROCEDURES SET FORTH.  THE DRIVER WAS WARNED FOR HIS FAILURE TO BE IN ATTENDANCE WHILE UNLOADING, AND I WILL REWRITE COMPANY POLICIES ALSO, TO HOPEFULLY DETER SUCH NEGLIGENCE IN THE FUTURE.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM MORGAN STATE UNIVERSITY LOCATED AT 1701 COLD SPRING LANE IN BALTIMORE, MD TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE WITH SPEEDI DRY AND TIGHTENED THE BUNG CAP WHICH WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LOOSE.  ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS WAS CONTAINERIZED AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  ALL LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO OVERPACK ANY CONTAINER THAT IS FOUND TO BE NOT STRUCTURALLY SOUND.  IN ADDITION, LOADING PERSONNEL WILL BE RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ALL CLOSURE DEVICES ARE PROPERLY SECURED PRIOR TO SHIPMENT.

LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DISPOSAL FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED ONTO THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT PAD OF THE VEHICLE PARKING AREA FROM THE ANCILLARY PIPING ASSOCIATED WITH THE VEHICLES SCRUBBER UNIT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND PROCEEDED TO DRAIN THE ANCILLARY PIPING.  ALL MATERIAL DRAINED FROM THE PIPING SYSTEM WAS PLACED IN THE CARGO TANK FOR DISPOSAL AT THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER.  IN ADDITION, ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS WAS CONTAINERIZED AND DISPOSED OF ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL SHIPMENT.  INSPECTION OF THE PIPING SYSTEM IDENTIFIED A SMALL CRACK IN THE WELD OF ONE OF THE PIPES.  THE UNIT WAS UNLOADED AND IMMEDIATELY SENT FOR REPAIRS PRIOR TO BEING PLACED BACK IN SERVICE.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE LOAD AND VEHICLE WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DRAINAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO PERFORM A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION ON EACH VEHICLE BEING OPERATED AND WILL TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A DEFECT IS DISCOVERED.

LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

column168: A PASSING TRAIN CREW OBSERVED TANK CAR LEAKING IN YARD.  SHIPPER'S RESPONSE TEAM FOUND A DEFECTIVE MANWAY GASKET WHICH WAS REPLACED.  AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE, THE SHIPPER HAD THE CAR RETURNED TO THE NEAR BY LOADING FACILITY TO REDUCE THE LOAD.  THE CAR DID NOT APPEAR TO BE OVERLOADED; HOWEVER, DAILY HIGH TEMPS WERE EXCEEDING 100 DEGREES F. PRODUCT EVAPORATED RAPIDLY FROM CAR SIDES.

A MEMBER OF THE YARD SWITCH CREW DETECTED AN ODOR COMING FROM THIS CAR WHILE WALKING A CUT OF CARS AT THE WEST END OF YARD TRACK 141.  THE SHIPPER'S RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO ASSESS THE CAR.  THE VALVE PLUGS WERE NOT IN PLACE AND THE VALVES WERE FOUND TO BE OPEN.  THE CAR HAD BEEN DEPRESSURIZED ATTHEIR FACILITY BUT WAS CONTINUING TO VENT VAPOR.  THE VALVES WERE CLOSED AND THE PLUGS APPLIED SO THAT THE CAR COULD BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY.  THE SWITCHMAN THAT DISCOVERED THE TANK CAR REPORTED DISCOMFORT FROM HAVING BEEN OVERCOME BY INHALING THE VAPORS.  HE WAS TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR AN EXAM WHERE THE DIAGNOSIS INDICATED A SORE THROAT AND CHEST PAIN ACCOUNT CONTACT WITH THE VAPORS.  X-RAYS WERE TAKEN WHICH WERE NEGATIVE FOR LUNG DAMAGE.  THE DOCTOR RELEASED THE EMPLOYEE TO FULL DUTY WITH INSTRUCTIONS TO GARGLE WITH SALT WATER AND TO TAKE TYLENOL IF NEEDED.  A FOLLOW UP EXAMINATIN FOR CONTINUED IRRITATION OF THE THROAT AND LUNGS INCLUDED AND INJECTION, A PRESCRIPTION AND A RELEASE OF DUTY. NO LOST TIME RESULTED FROM THIS INCIDENT.  THE SHIPPER HAS RECENLTY PRESENTED A PROGRAM FOR THE RAILWAYS CREWS THAT ADDRESSED RAIL SHIPMENT OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA.  THE EMPLOYEE WAS IN ATTENDANCE AT THE

SOMETHING DAMAGED THIS DRUM - IT WAS BENT. IN THE CREASE OF THE BEND, THE DRUM HAD A 3/4 INCH CRACK. THE CRACK WAS NOT OPEN ENOUGH TO ALLOW THE DRIP. THE DRUM WOULD ONLY LEAK WHEN IT WAS DISTURBED. WE CONCLUDED THE MATERIAL HAD SPURTED OUT THE DRUM WHEN THE TRAILER ROLLED OVER BUMPS ON THE ROAD. IF WE DISTURBED THE DRUM, A DROP OR TWO WOULD FALL FROM THE CRACK. THE CRACK WAS SEALED WITH EPOXY, AND THE CRYSTALIZED SPILL WAS PICKED UP BY THE CARDBOARD IT WAS ON. BOTH THE DAMAGED DRUM AND SPILLED MATERIAL WERE SEALED IN RECOVERY DRUMS.

column168: RAILCAR NUMBER ACFX84620 HAD BEEN DELIVERED THE PREVIOUS DAY.  THE CAR HAD BEEN SPOTTED OVER RAIL UNLOADING PIT IN ORDER TO BEGIN UNLOADING.  MIKE AND DAVE WERE IN THE PROCESS OF REMOVING THE CAP TO HOOK THE HOSE TO THE UNLOADING FITTING.  WHEN THE VALVE WAS UNSCREWED, THE FORCE OF THE LIQUID PUSHED THE CAP OUT OF MIKE'S HAND AND THE MATERIAL BEGAN RUNNING OUT OF THE CAR. DAVE CLIMBED TO THE TOP OF THE RAILCAR AND REMOVED THE PITHOG AND FASTENED THE DOME LID IN HOPE OF CREATING A VACUUM TO STOP THE FLOW OUT OF THE CAR.  DAVE CALLED DAN HOLDNACK AND CHAD ROTH.  HE WAS INFORMED TO LET THE MATERIAL RUN INTO CONTAINMENT UNTIL IT SLOWED ENOUGH TO REPLACE THE CAP WITHOUT RISK OF INJURY.  AFTER APPROXIMATELY 1/2 HOUR THE FLOW HAD SLOWED ENOUGH TO PUT THE CAP BACK ON THE OUTLET.  8,200 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WERE RELEASED INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA PRIOR TO THE FLOW BEING STOPPED.  DAVE HAD ALSO PLACED A HOSE INTO THE TANK DIKE AND BEGAN PUMPING THE MATERIAL INTO THE STORAGE TANKS. MATERIAL WAS PUMPED INTO STORAGE TANKS, TANK DIKE WAS WIPED DOWN WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND LACQUER THINNER. ENTIRE CLEANUP LASTED APPROXIMATELY 6 HOURS.

THIS PACKAGE DID NOT FAIL. THE TANK WAS NOT DAMAGED.  THE TANK HAS ALREADY BEEN SHIPPED BACK TO SHIPPER.  HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST NOT AVAILABLE AT THIS TIME.

A MARINE PORTABLE TANK, LEADED AT CROWLEY, LA.  WAS ON BOARD THE VESSEL NORMAND MCCALL, WHEN A PIN-HOLE LEAK DEVELOPED IN THE BOTTOM OF THE MPT. THE MPT WAS OFF LOADED FROM THE VESSEL ONTO THE MOBILE EXP PLATFORM.  THE PIN-HOLE LEAK WAS EXAMINED AND APPEARED TO BE GETTING BIGGER WHEN AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO PLUG THE LEAK. THE PLUGGING EFFORT FAILED AND MORE LADING WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE MPT.  TO PROTECT THE PLATFORM'S PERSONNEL AND EQUIPMENT FROM THE LEAKING HYDROCHLORIC ACID, THE MPT WAS SWUNG OFF THE PLATFORM BY THE CRANE AND ALLOWED TO EMPTY ITSELF INTO THE OPEN WATERS OF THE GULF.  THE US COAST GUARD IN GALVESTON, TX WAS NOTIFIED AS WAS THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE TEXAS STATE ENVIRONMENTAL EMER.  RESPONSE GROUP.  REGION 12.

column168: ON SEPTEMBER 4, 1995, A 1971 INTERNATIONAL TRUCK WAS TRAVELING EAST ON MT. 80 TOWARD GERALDINE.  BETWEEN MILE POST 8 AND 9 THE TRUCK ENTERED A SERIES OF "S" CURVES KNOWN AS BOYLE COULEE.  THE VEHICLE ENTERED A CURVE ON A DOWN HILL GRADE AND DRIFTED TO THE RIGHT OFF THE PAVEMENT ONTO THE SHOULDER. THE DRIVER THEN ATTEMPTED TO BRING THE VEHICLE BACK ONTO THE ROADWAY AND OVER CORRECTED CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO SLIDE.  THE TRUCK CROSSED BOTH LANES OF TRAFFIC AND OVERTURNED IN THE WEST BOUND LANES BORROW PIT. THE TRUCK WAS THEN INVOLVED IN A POST ACCIDENT FIRE AND TOTALLY DESTROYED. AT SOME POINT THE CARGO BED SEPARATED FROM THE FRAME AND CONTINUED TO TRAVEL DOWN THE ROAD COMING TO REST ON THE PAVEMENT. THERE WAS A RELEASE OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA FROM THE TANKS THROUGH BROKEN SAFETY VALVES.  SEE ATTACHED DRAWING OF ACCIDENT SCENE.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM THE STOLLE CORPORATION LOCATED 2615 CAMBELL ROAD IN SIDNEY, OH TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DISPOSAL FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1.5 QUARTS OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP BUNG OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT PAD OF THE VEHICLE PARKING AREA.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND TIGHTENED THE BUNG CAP OF THE DRUM IN QUESTION.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS CONTAINERIZED AND PLACED INTO STORAGE PENDING DISPOSAL THROUGH THE RECEIVING FACILITY IDENTIFIED ON THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS UNLOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.  IN ADDITION, DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT ALL CLOSURES TO INSURE THEY ARE ADEQUATELY SECURED.

THE ROCKFORD FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT UNIT WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED AND DISPATCHED TO THE SPILL SITE TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. TGIX 120, RESIDUE SUPLHUR CAR, NOTED WITH SMOKE AND FLAME COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL NOTIFIED.  INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THE SMOLDERING FIRE WAS ORIGINATING BETWEEN THE TANK SHELL AND THE JACKET AND THAT IT WAS SULPHUR BURNING IN THE INSULATION SPACE.  THE SMOKE AND FLAME WERE COMING THROUGH A CRACK IN THE CAR'S JACKET.  THE SOURCE OF THE SULPHUR IS UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME.  THERE WERE NO INDICATIONS THAT THE TANK ITSELF WAS LEAKING. POSSILY THE SULPHUR HAD BUILT-UP OVER TIME FROM PRODUCT LOSS DURING THE LOADING THE LOADING PROCESS.  THE SOURCE OF IGNITION FOR THE FIRE IS ALSO UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME.  LOCAL FIRE PERSONNEL EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE, THE CAR WAS SECURED AND TRANSFERRED TO THE TANK CAR REPAIR FACILITY FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION AS TO THE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT AND FOR REPAIRS TO THE DAMAGE.

MPC FOUND LIQUID PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE 2" PLUG ON ONE OF THE LIQUID VALVES. MPC OPENED AND CLOSED THE LIQUID VALVE (BALL VALVE) TO RESEAT IT AND NOTED VALVE OPERATED TO EASILY. THE CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL FOUND THAT LIQUID PRODUCT WAS TRAPPED BETWEEN THE BALL VALVE AND VALVE PLUG ON THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE. THE LINE WAS DRAINED AND THE PLUG INSTALLED AND TIGHTENED. BEFORE LEAVING FINA TRUCK STOP, THE DRIVER OF U.S. POLLUTION CONTROL, INC. CONDUCTED A PRE-TRIP VEHICLE INSPECTION AND NOTICED A MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE VAN TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS HAD LEAKED ON THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT OF THE TRUCK STOP. THE MATERIAL WAS DESCRIBED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER AS "RQ HAZARDOUS WASTE, SOLIDS, N.O.S., (XYLENE, TOLUENE), 9, NA 3077, PG III (F002, F003, F005, D018, D021, D025, D039)."  FIVE OF THE SEVENTEEN PACKAGES CONTAINING THIS MATERIAL WERE LEAKING. PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION, THE MATERIAL WAS IN A SOLID FORM AND WAS PACKED IN FIBERBOARD BOXES. THESE BOXES WERE DESIGNATED TO CONTAIN SOLID MATERIALS. DURING THE TRANSIT, THE MATERIAL BECAME LIQUEFIED. AS A RESULT, FIVE OF THE SEVENTEEN BOXES LEAKED. A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS CONTACTED. THE VAN TRAILER AND CONTAMINATED AREA WAS CLEANED UP. HYDROCARBONS RECYCLES, INC. WAS INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT. IT WILL CONDUCT A THOROUGH INSPECTION BEFORE SHIPPING THE MATERIAL IN THE FUTURE. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS CONTACTED SINCE THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY (TEN POUNDS) OF EPA WASTE CODE D018 WAS RELEASED.

THE AREA WAS SECURED BY N.M STATE POLICE AND THE CLEAN UP WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY ASARCO PERSONAL FROM AMARILLO REFINERY, THE ESCAPE ROUTE OF THE LIQUID WAS SEALED WITH SILICONE SEALER AND TAR THEN INSPECTED BY THE N.M. STATE POLICE AND ALLOWED TO CONTINUE TO THE DESTINATION.  FULL COVER TARPS HAVE BEEN REDESIGNED TO PREVENT ANY RAIN WATER FROM ENTERING THE TRAILER AND ALL INTERIOR SEAM CRACKS WELDED AND INSPECTED TO INSURE PROPER SEAL TO THE INTERIOR AREA.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0945 HOURS ON SEPTEMBER 6, MATLACK TRUCK DRIVER/ OPERATOR WAS LOADING ONE OF THREE COMPARTMENTS IN TRAILER SP 6998 WITH XYLENE AT THE WEST ALBANY YARD FLEXI-FLO SITE.  THE DRIVER'S INSTRUCTIONS FROM HIS DISPATCHER SHOWED THAT HE WAS TO LOAD 4,500 GALLONS BUT THE COMPARTMENT ONLY HAD A CAPACITY OF 4,100 GALLONS.  CONRAILS FACILITY OPERATOR, BULK TRANSLOAD SERVICES, REPORTS THAT CAPACITY WAS NOT MARKED ON EACH COMPARTMENT AND THAT THE DRIVER COULD NOT READ/UNDERSTAND THE CAPACITY CHART ON THE TANK.  THE DRIVER CLEANED THE CONTAINMENT BOX AND THEN CONTINUED HIS ASSIGNMENT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: HALLIBURTON EMPLOYEE "A" FILLED TWO SEPARATE CUSTOMER ORDERS FROM THE EXPLOSIVE MAGAZINE AT APPROXIMATELY 0830, A TOTAL OF FOUR BOXES.  CUSTOMER "1" PICKED UP THEIR ORDER (2 BOXES).  CUSTOMER "2" CALLED AND CANCELLED ORDER FOR REMAINING TWO BOXES.  BEFORE THE CANCELLED ORDER COULD BE RETURNED TO THE MAGAZINE, HALINBURTON EMPLOYEE "B" USED THE PICKUP TO RUN A COMPANY ERRAND.  THE TAILGATE WAS DOWN AND THE BOXES FELL OUT OF THE BACK OF THE PICKUP DURING TRANSIT.  AFTER RETURNING FROM HIS ERRAND IT WAS DISCOVERED THE BOXES HAD FALLEN OUT.  RETRACING THEIR PATH ONE BOX OF EXPLOSIVES WAS FOUND INTACT.  THE OTHER BOX HAD BEEN STRUCK BY ANOTHER VEHICLE AND THE BROUSSARR POLICE DEPARTMENT WAS ON WAS ON THE SCENE PICKING UP THE LOOSE CHARGES.  THE EXPLOSIVE DIVISION OF THE LA STATE POLICE WAS CALLED AND A SEARCH WAS CONDUCTED USING 20 HALLIBURTON EMPLOYEES, MEMBERS OF THE BROUSSARD FIRE & POLICE DEPARTMENT, AND AN EXPLOSIVE TRAINED DOG.  89 OF THE 100 CHARGES WERE RECOVERED.  AFTER A TOTAL OF THREE HOURS THE LA STATE POLICE CALLED OFF THE SEARCH.  EMPLOYEES OF THE BROUSSARD LOCATION HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED ON THE PROPER PROCEDURES FOR THE LOADING AND TRANSPORTATION OF EXPLOSIVE.

column14: PARK ROAD AT SAM ALLEN ROAD
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: SEMI TRACTOR TANKER WAS NORTH BOUND ON PARK ALLEN ROAD, AT APPROXIMATELY 40 MPH ACCORDING TO WITNESS.  DRIVER WHO HAD BEEN OFF DUTY THE TWO PREVIOUS DAYS AND ON DUTY FOR THREE AND ONE HALF (3 1/2) HOURS ADVISED THAT HE APPARENTLY DOZED OFF.  DRIVER FAILED TO SLOW OR STOP FOR SIGN AND ON ROUSING UP AT THE "T" INTERSECTION.  ATTEMPTED TO MAKE A 90 DEGREE LEFT TURN, RESULTING IN THE UNIT ROLLING OVER ONE AND ONE HALF TURNS.  DURING ROLLOVER, DIRT AND DEBRIS IN THE ROLLOVER PROTECTION BOX BROKE THE 3/4 INCH AIR PRESSURE BLEED OFF LINE, ALLOWING SOME PRODUCT TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND.  C.T.L. column168: ON SEPTEMBER 27, 1995, JOSE CARRILLO, DRIVER FOR SIERRA CHEMICAL COMPANY WAS DOING DELIVERIES AND PICK UPS IN THE BA AREA.  HE PICKED UP NINE, FIFTEEN GALLON, CARBOYS OF SULFURIC ACID, AT HOLCHEM IN OAKLAND, TO DELIVER TO PETOSEED IN WOODLAND.  JOSE WAS ON 98TH AND BIGG WHEN HE HAD TO HIT HIS BRAKE BECAUSE OF TRAFFIC.  BECAUSE THE BARBOYS WERE NOT TIED DOWN SECURELY, THEY SAID FORWARD.  SCREWS PROTRUDING FROM THE FLOOR BOARDS CUT TWO OF THE CARBOYS AND THEY STARED LEAKING. JOSE IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER AT A VACANT LOT TO CHECK HIS CARGO.  HE DISCOVERED ONE LEAKING CARBOY AND TIPPED IT OVER TO STOP THE LEAKING.  (THE OTHER CARBOY HAD A VERY SMALL TEAR AND MINIMAL LEAKAGE AND WAS DISCOVERED AND CONTAINED BY MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL)  JOSE THEN SET UP WARNING TRIANGLE AROUND THE TRUCK AND WENT TO A NEARBY BUSINESS TO USE THEIR PHONE TO CONTACT THE COMPANY OFFICE AND REPORTED THE SITUATION.  HE OBTAINED A BAG OF ABSORBENT AND POURED IT ON AND AROUND THE SPILL THUS CONTAINING IT.  BY THIS TIME, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD ARRIVED AND INFORMED JOSE HE HAD TO HOURS TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  STEVE GOULD RECEIVED THE PHONE CALL FROM JOSE.  HE FIRST CALLED HOLCHEM, OUR SUPPLIER OF THE PRODUCT, AND ASKED IF THEY WOULD ASSIST IN THE CLEAN UP, BUT THEY DID NOT WANT TO GET INVOLVED.  STEVE THEN CALLED MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL AND THEY ARRIVED ON THE SCENE, CONTAINED THE TWO CARBOYS AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE.  JOSE LEFT AROUND 6:15 PM AND DROVE DIRECTLY BACK TO SIERRA CHEMICAL COMPANY.

column168: WE WERE DELIVERING 6,000 GALLONS OF PETOIL H-100 TO NASHUA CHEMICAL.  THE PRODUCT IS TRANSFERRED FROM OUT TANK TRAILER TO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE BY SUING THE CUSTOMER PUMP.  IN ADDITION TO THE PUMP, AIR PRESSURE (ALSO SUPPLIED BY THE CUSTOMER) WAS APPLIED TO THE TRAILER.  LIQUID CARGO SUPPLIED A 3" HOSE WHICH CONNECTED THE TRAILER TO THE PUMP. APPROXIMATELY, 10 MINUTES INTO THE TRANSFER, THE HOSE RUPTURED BEHIND THE CONNECTION AT THE PUMP.  IT IS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY PLANT PERSONNEL.  THEY USED 40-50# BAGS OF SPEEDY DRY ABSORBANT.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND SPEEDY DRY WERE PUT INTO 20-55 GALLONS DRUMS.  ARRANGEMENTS ARE BEING MADE TO HAVE THE PRODUCT DISPOSED OF AS NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE.

UPON ARRIVAL AT TRUCK STOP, DRIVER NOTICED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM REAR OF TRAILER.  TRAILER WAS SEALED AND DRIVER DID NOT POSSESS PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, SO A RESPONSE CREW WAS CONTRACTED TO EVALUATE THE SITUATION AND PERFORM THE NECESSARY WORK TO REMEDY THE PROBLEM.  THE RESPONSE CREW FOUND THREE (3) CONTAINERS, A 5 GALLON, 15 GALLON, AND 55 GALLON LEAKING INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THOSE WERE PLACED INTO OVERPACK DRUMS. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED INSIDE TRAILER ON STEEL SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN.  ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS PLACED ON SPILLED MATERIAL AND THEN PLACED IN OVERPACK DRUM.  LEAKAGE FROM THE 3 CONTAINERS WAS CAUSED BY LOOSE OR CRACKED BUNGS.  LOAD PROCESSED TO DESTINATION WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEMS.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO, INC.  LOCATED AT 11800 SOUTH STONEY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO, IL TO PHIBRO-TECH, INC.  LOCATED AT 10 INDUSTRY AVENUE INJOILET, IL.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER WAS STOPPED AND INSPECTED BY THE ILLINOIS DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION.  THE OFFICER CONDUCTING THE INSPECTION IDENTIFIED THAT APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP BUNG OF ONE OF THE DRUMS ONTO THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE RETURNED TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION WHERE THE TOP OF THE DRUM WAS CLEANED USING ABSORBANT PADS AND THE BUNG CAP WAS REPLACED AND SECURED.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINERIZED AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO, INC.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINER WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED. ALL LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO OVERPACK ANY CONTAINER THAT IS FOUND TO BE NOT STRUCTURALLY SOUND.  IN ADDITION, DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT ALL CLOSURES TO INSURE THEY ARE ADEQATELY SECURED.

IMMEDIATELY HE RUSHED BACK TO CLOSE THE INTERNAL VALVE AND THEN THE EXTERNAL VALVE SHUTTING OFF THE PRODUCT APPROX. 3-5 GALLONS OF OMS WAS SPILLED IN A CONTAINED AREA.  THE PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AT THE CUSTOMER SITE, NEED TO ENSURE TANKS ARE DEPRESSURIZED BEFORE UNLOADING.

column168: ON 09/01/95 AT APPROXIMATELY 0359 HOURS, I, KAREN NICHOLS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON OH 45177 INVESTIGATED A SHIPMENT IN OUR SORT FAILITY OF THE SAME ADDRESS. THE SHIPMENT WAS EMITTING AN ODOR THAT CAUSED AN EMPLOYEE TO BE LIGHT HEADED.  THIS EMPLOYEE RECEIVED NO MEDICAL TREATMENT.  THE SHIMENT WAS PACKAGED IN A FIBREBOARD BOX WITH NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS ON IT. THERE WAS NO SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT.  INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX I FOUND 48 X 8 OZ METAL CANS WITH FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES OF A FLAMMABLE LIQUID USED UNDER STEAM TABLE TRAYS. ON THE CANS THE LABELS READ "FLAMMABLE.  CONTAINS METHYL ALCOHOL". APPROXIMATELY 8 TOTAL 0Z OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM AN UNDETERMINED NUMBER OF THE METAL CANS.  THE METAL CANS WERE NOT DAMAGED.  THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES TO THE METAL CANS AND THERE WERE 3 LOOSE CLOSURES.  ALSO INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX WERE SEVERAL FOIL STEAM TABLE TRAYS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD IN OUR HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.  SIGNATURE OF PERSON FILING REPORT:

SAHM MEZA RESPONDED AND FOUND THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING A WHITE FOAMING PRODUCT FROM THE REAR DOORS OF THE TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED THE TRAILER TO A SECURE AREA AT THE EAST SIDE OF THE PORT.  SAHM MEZA CALLED CODE 3 INC.  TO ASSIST WITH THE RESPONSE. ENTRY WAS MADE AND IT WAS NOTED THAT TWO 55 GALLON DRUMS HAD OVERTURNED AND PRODUCT WAS LEAKING. column168: ON SEPTEMBER 14,1995, AT APPROXIMATELY 12:15PM, OUR DRIVER JONNIE EVANS WAS ENROUTE FROM HAMMOND, IN. TO REMINGTON, IN. MR. EVANS WAS TAKING THE RAMP FROM EASTBOUND I-90 TO SOUTHBOUND I-65, WHEN HE CAME TO A SHARP CURVE IN THE RAMP, AT THIS POINT THE TRACTOR-TRAILER FELL OVER ONTO IT'S RIGHT SIDE AND SLID INTO THE OVER-HEAD BRIDGE SUPPORTS. ENVIROMENTAL TO TRANSFER THE REMAINING PART OF THE LOAD TO ANOTHER UNIT AND START THE ENVIROMENTAL CLEAN-UP. ON THIS DAY MR. EVANS HAD A TRAINEE RIDING WITH HIM, JAMES ILION. BOTH THE DRIVER AND PASSENGER WENT TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL WITH CUTS. THEY WERE TREATED AND RELEASED. WE FEEL THIS ACCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY DRIVER NEGLIGENCE.

THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OH 45177.  UPON OUR INVESTIGATION OF THE SHIPMENT, WE DISCOVERED A PLAIN BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX.  AFTER OPENING THE BOX, WE FOUND TWO SMALLER BOXES CONTAINING 8 GLASS RECEPTACLES OF RESIN SOLUTION.  ONE OF THE GLASS RECEPTACLES WAS BROKEN. column168: ON SEPTEMBER 1, 1995, AROUND 6:15 PM, WILL HORSLEY, A DRIVER OF LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TG), INC., PULLED UP TO TOLL-BOOTH ON I-77 AT EXIT 28 IN GHENT, WEST VIRGINIA.  THE TOLL-BOOTH OPERATOR INSTRUCTED THE LAIDLAW DRIVER TO PULL OVER ON THE SIDE BECAUSE THERE WAS AN ODOR COMING FROM THE CARGO TANK.  THE LAIDLAW DRIVER INSPECTED THE CARGO TANK AND FOUND THAT SOME MATERIAL HAD APPEARED TO LEAK FROM THE DISCHARGE CAP.  THE LAIDLAW DRIVER THEN PLACED A RAG AND PLASTIC MATERIAL AROUND THE CAP AND TAPED IT IN PLACE.  APPROXIMATELY 15 PERSON, INCLUDING THE LAIDLAW DRIVER, INHALED THE VAPORS FROM THE CARGO TANK.  THE LAIDLAW DRIVER NEVER EXPERIENCED ANY PROBLEMS.  ONLY ONE OF THE PERSONS WHO INHALED VAPORS WAS ADMITTED TO A HOSPTIAL OVER NIGHT FOR OBSERVATION, AND THE OTHERS WERE TREATED AT THE SCENE OR WERE RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL EMERGENCY ROOM AFTER BEING CHECKED OUT.  THERE WERE SEVERAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS CALLED OUT TO THE SCENE.  THEY WERE AS FOLLOWS:  WEST VIRGINIA STATE POLICE; WEST VIRGINIA PARKWAY SAFETY DEPARTMENT; EVERGREEN ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT; JAN CARE AMBULANCE SERVICE, AND DUPONT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM.  EVERGREEN ENVIRONMENTAL MANGEMENT REPLACED A MISSING GASKET ON THE DISCHARGE CAP, WHICH STOPPED THE VAPORS FROM BEING RELEASED.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS CONTACTED AT APPROXIMATELY 4:40 PM ON SEPTEMBER 1, 1995 (REPORT #306472).  LAIDLAW WAS ALSO CONTACTED BY THE NATIONAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY BOARD ON SEPTEMBER 6, 1995.  LAIDLAW PROVIDED ALL DETAILS THAT WERE AVAILABLE AT THAT TIME.  NTSB CONTACT:  JAMES HENDERSON (202) 382-6815.

ON SEPTEMBER 21, 1995, MARY LATHAM, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT LEAD, REPORTED A SPILL WITH AN ODOR.  THE SPILL WAS LOCATED AT OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR ADDIE CAMPTON AND SPILL TECHNICIANS DAVID JARRELL AND CAROLYN CORDREY RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL WE FOUND A WET FIBREBOARD BOX.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE INNER CONTENTS WE FOUND TWO (2) ONE (1) GALLON METAL RECEPTACLES WITH FRICTION-TYPE CLOSURES. WHILE INSPECTING THE INNER RECEPTACLES WE DISCOVERED BOTH RECEPTACLES HAD BEEN POSSIBLY CRUSHED ON THEIR SIDES AND DENTS TO THE CLOSURES.  THE ONLY OTHER INNER PACKING MATERAIL WAS A CARDBOARD DIVIDER.  THIS SHIIPMENT CONTAINED NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE OUTER PACKAGE WAS CLEARLY MARKED AND LABELED AS THE FOLLOWING:  "FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S.", "UN 1993".  THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND ALL PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELS APPLIED.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS POSSIBLE FRICTION AND RUBBING OF OTHER FREIGHT RESULTING IN POSSIBLE CRUSHING OF THE SHIPMENT CAUSING CLOSURE FAILURE.  WE WERE CLEAR OF SCENE AT 0412.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: ON SEPT 26, 1995, RON LOPEZ, SORT SPVR AT ABX AIR, INC., LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVER, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177, REPORTED A SPILL.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR, ADDIE CAMPTON AND SPILL TECHNICIAN, JEFF MCLAUGHLIN RESPONSDED.  UPON OUR ARRIVAL WE FOUND A PLAIN BROWN FIBREBOARD BOX WAS SETTING IN A YELLOW LIQUID.  THE BOX AL AIRWAY BILL AND A PRE-PRINTED PUROLATOR LABEL ON THE TOP OF THE BOX, ATTACHED TO THE SIDE OF THE BOX WAS MATERAIL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  AFTER REMOVING THE CONTENTS OF THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED A CONSUMER COMMODITY "PAINT", WHICH IS REGULATED BY AIR.  WE CONTINUE DOING OUR INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS AND FOUND (2) METAL ONE-GALLON CONTAINERS WITH FRICTION-TYPE CLOSURES, ONE OF WHICH HAD LEAKED ALL OF ITS CONTENTS.  THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL OR CUSHIONING MATERIAL CONTAINED WITHIN THE PKG.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABLED TO INDICATE THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL AND THE PROPER CERTIFICATION DID NOT ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS POSSIBLE RUBBING AND FRICTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS CAUSING THE CLOSURE TO FAIL ON ONE OF THE METAL RECEPTACLES. THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING A FAA INVESTIGATION.  WHEN THIS SHIPMENT IS RELEASED, WE WILL RETURN TO THE SHIPPER OR MOVE ONTO DESTINATION PER THE SHIPPERS REQUEST. CLEAR OF SCENE 0407.

ON SEPTEMBER 20,1995, AT 0303, TOM ARCHIBALD, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT SUPERVISOR, REPORTED AN ODOR AT THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR, ADDIE CAMPTON, AND SPILL TECHNICIANS, DAVID JARRELL AND CAROLY CORDEREY, RESPONDED.  UPON OUR ARRIVAL WE FOUND FOUR (4) FIBREBOARD BOXES ALL PART OF THE SAME SHIPMENT.  WE FOUND NOTHING WRONG WITH THE OUTER BOXES.  HOWEVER, UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS OF THE BOXES, WE DISCOVERED ONE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE ENCLOSED IN A PLASTIC BAG.  THAT WAS LEAKING APPROXIMATELY 1 OZ. OF LIQUID IN THE SEALED BAG.  THE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE THAT LEAKED HAD NO CUSHIONING OR ABSORBENT MATERIAL PACKED INSIDE THE BAG.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS CLEARLY MARKED AND LABELED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AS FOLLOWS:  "RESIN SOLUTION", "FLAMMABLE" "UN 1866".  DUE TO THE LEAKAGE AND ODOR, THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED IN A RECOVERY DRUM WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THE PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELS WERE APPLIED AND THE PROPER CERTIFICATION WAS ATTACHED.  THE ONLY THEORY FOR FAILURE OF THIS PACKAGE WAS POSSIBLE RUBBING, ABRADING AND FRICTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS, CAUSING THE INNER CONTENTS TO LEAK.  CLEAR OF SCENE AT 0342.

FOR THE FURTHER INSPECTION, HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIAN SHARON LOVE DONNED PPE AND AN SCBA, SEVERAL SHIPMENTS IN THE C CONTAINER WERE OPENED TO CHECK FOR SIGNS OF LEAKAGE THAT WOULD CAUSE THE ODOR.  NO SOURCE WAS FOUND AT THIS TIME. 13:07 CLEAR OF SCENE.  13:50 DURING THE RELOADING OF THE FREIGHT REMOVED FROM THE BLUE C CONTAINER SHARON NOTICED LIQUID ON TOP OF THE BOXES.  SHE NOTIFIED FRAN VANCE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR, FRAN DONNED PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, OPENED THE TOP OF THE BOX AND FOUND VERMICULITE,2 METAL CONTAINERS IN HERMATICALLY SEALED PLASTIC BAGS.  THERE WAS NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE FROM THE TOP INSIDE THE INNER PACKAGING MATERIAL SHOWED SIGNS OF MOISTURE, NO PH READING COULD BE OBTAINED, THE MOISTURE WAS MORE IN THE FORM OF AN OIL TYPE STAIN.  THERE WAS A BROWN LIQUID INSIDE THE PLASTIC BAGS AND THE BOTTOM OF THE INNER METAL CONTAINERS WERE COMPROMISED BY MEANS OF POSSIBLE INTERNAL PRESSURE.  THE BOTTOM OF BOTH CONTAINERS WERE COMPROMISED BY MEANS OF POSSIBLE INTERNAL PRESSURE.  THE BOTTOM OF BOTH CONTAINERS WERE BUILDING AND SMALL DENTS WERE ALONG THE SEAM.  THE INFORMATION WAS RECORDED OFF THE INNER AND OUTER CONTAINERS.  ALDRICCH CHEMICAL COMPANY HAS OBTAINED A COMPETENT AUTHORITY TO TRANSPORT THIS CHEMICAL UNTIL OCTOBER 1, 1995.  ADDITIONAL ASSISTANCE WAS REQUESTED, AREA SURROUNDING THE SHIPMENT WAS BARRICADED, DEON AREA SET UP, ABX FIBREBRIGADE MEMBERS WITH RESPONSE EQUIPMENT STANDING BY FOR PRECAUTIONARY MEASURES, HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIANS ARRIVED SPILL PERSONELL WERE BRIEFED TO THE SITUATION, PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT WAS DONNED, SPILL TEAM ENTERED, SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A POLY DRUM, SPILL TEAM WAS DECONNED, SHIPMENT WAS TAKEN OUT OF THE HAZ MAT AREA AND PLACED IN AN AREA AWAY FROM ALL PERSONNEL AND EQUIPMENT UNTIL ALDRICH MAKES ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE SHIPMENT PICKED UP BY AN OUTSIDE TRUCKING AGENCY FOR RETURN TO ALDRICH. EQUIPMENT USED WAS ALSO PLACED INSIDE A POLY DRUM AND PLACED IN THE SAME LOCATION AS THE SHIPMENT FOR RETURN TO ALDRICH.

THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM ON TOP OF THE FACILITY WAREHOUSE.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM WERE RELEASED ONTO A CONCRETE PAD AND ADJACENT CALICHE PARKING AREA.  THE AREA WAS SECURED AND ALL PERSONNEL IN THE FACILITY WERE NOTIFIED.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, HAZMAT OF TEXAS, WAS SUMMONED AND THE CONDITION OF AN ADDITIONAL 41 DRUMS OF PHOSPHORIC ACID WAS EVALUATED.  A CALICHE BERM WAS CONSTRUCTED TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE AREA AND PREVENT FURTHER SPREADING. THE EMERGENCY CONTACT PERSON FOR THE GENERATOR, MATT TOKHEIM MANGER-EHS GENERAL TIRE, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RELIEVED PRESSURE ON FOUR (4) DRUMS, USING A REMOTE DEVICE, WHICH HAD BULGING TOPS AND/OR BOTTOMS.  THE FOUR DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED, PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED ON THE REMAINING DRUMS, AND ALL DRUMS WERE TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE GENERATOR.  THE SPILL SITE IS BEING CLEANED AND THE WASTE REEVALUATED FOR PROPER SHIPMENT TO PREVENT FUTURE PROBLEMS.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: AFTER TAKING STICK READINGS, I HOOKED UP THE 2700 GALLON COMPARTMENT OF ECONOMY GAS, AND STARTED TO DROP. AS GAS WAS GOING INTO TANK, I PUT INFORMATION INTO THE TRIP MASTER SYSTEM. WHEN I GOT DONE, I GOT ANOTHER HOSE TO START THE ULTRA. I HOLLIED UP THE 2100 GALLON COMPARTMENT OF ULTRA, AND STARTED TO DROP GAS INTO ULTRA TANK. I THEN WALKED OVER TO THE BUCKET BOX OF THE TRAILER, AND AT THAT POINT THE HOSE THAT WAS CONNECTED TO THE ECONOMY FILL JUMPED OFF. THE HOSE HAD BEEN HOOKED UP, AND HAD BEEN GOING INTO THE TANK. WHEN I SAW WHAT WAS HAPPENING, I WENT OVER TO SHUT THE VALVE I SLIPPED AND HIT THE RIGHT SIDE OF MY HEAD. I DON'T KNOW IF I WAS STUNNED OR KNOCKED OUT, BUT WHEN I GOT MY SENSES BACK I WAS ON MY KNEES IN GASOLINE. I SHUT THE VALVE OFF AND GRABBED THE SPILL PADS AND STARTED TO PUT THEM OUT ON ROUTE 30. THEN I WENT AND CALLED 911. THE POLICE CAME AND TOOK OVER. WHEN THE AMBULANCE CAME TO CHECK ME THEY WANTED ME TO GO TO THE HOSPITAL, BUT I DIDN'T WANT TO LEAVE THE TRUCK. I HAD BEEN USING THE SAME FITTING ALL NIGHT TO MAKE MY OTHER DELIVERIES. WHEN I PUT THE FITTING ON IT WAS TIGHT. I FINISHED DROPPING THE ULTRA, AND THEN WHEN I WAS DONE SWITCHED THE FITTING THAT I USED FOR THE ULTRA AND PUT IT ON THE ECONOMY TANK AND FINISHED UNLOADING PER INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE FIRE CHIEF. I ALSO BROKE A LENSE ON MY GLASSES.

column168: ON 092095 SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, RAUL MEZA WAS ADVISED THAT THERE WAS A LEAKING TANKCAR OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ON TRACK #9. MEZA IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED AND FROM A DISTANCE OBSERVED TANK CAR CELX11274 ON TRACK 009. HE NOTED THAT IT WAS PLACARDED UN1917, HE THEN MADE AN ATTEMPT TO GATHER PROPER EMERGENCY DOCUMENTATION VIA COMPUTER, BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL. THE TANKCAR WAS LISTED AS AN EMPTY WITH NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PER THE COMPUTER. HE THEN MADE CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER, HOECHST CELANESE IN BISHOP, TX. AND SPOKE TO PAT MOONEY. MOONEY REFERRED HIM TO THE HOUSTON, TX. PLANT. HE LATER RECEIVED A CALL FROM BOB PONJETTI. PONJETTI WAS ABLE TO VERIFY THAT THE TANKCAR WAS IN FACT AN EMPTY AND WAS BEING SHIPPED BACK FROM CELANESE IN MEXICO. HE STATED THAT THE TANKCAR SHOULD HAVE SOME RESIDUE AND SHOULD BE HANDLED WITH CARE. PONJETTI WAS ABLE TO PROVIDE HIM WITH TECHNICAL GUIDANCE IN CHECKING FOR A POSSIBLE RELEASE THE FITTINGS OF THE TANKCAR. HE THEN INSPECTED THE TANKCAR AND DISCOVERED THAT THE BOTTOM CAP AND PLUG, MANWAY COVER FLANGE NUTS, AND THE LIQUID VALVE FLANGE NUTS WERE LOOSE. THE VAPOR LEAK WAS STOPPED BY TIGHTENING ALL THE FLANGE NUTS. MEZA LATER SPOKE TO TEXAS MEXICAN RAILROAD'S MR. RODRIQUEZ WHO ADVISED THAT THE TANKCAR BELONGED TO THEM AND THAT IS WHY IT DID NOT SHOW PROPER BILLING IN OUR COMPUTER SYSTEM. ON 09/21/95 HE DISCUSSED THE SITUATION WITH MTO MIKE CHAVAZ. HE ADVISED THAT HE WOULD MEET WITH THE TEX. MEX. OFFICALS TO CORRECT THE PROBLEM. THE TANKCAR WILL BE BROUGHT BACK TO LAREDO, TEXAS AND INTERCHANGED TO THE TEX. MEX. RR.

IN THE HEAD END OF THE TRAILER THERE WERE DRUMS STACKED ON TOP OF DRUMS, THE TOP COURSE OF DRUMS HAD SHIFTED, ALLOWING TWO OF THE DRUMS TO COME IN CONTACT, THE MOTION OF THE CAR CAUSE THE DRUMS TO WEAR A HOLE IN THE CHIMES. ONE DRUM ABOUT TWO THIRDS EMPTY THE OTHER HALF EMPTY. THEY WERE REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER AND PATCHED, USING EPOXY STEEL, THE PATCH COVERED WITH ALUMINUM TAPE AND EPOXY GLUE. P & D DRIVER STEVEN BROWN PICKED UP VAT AT SHIPPER.  VAT WAS LOADED ON LEFT REAR OF TRAILER.  DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO ANOTHER STOP.  HE HAD DRIVEN ABOUT 8 MILES ON I215.  HE MERGED ONTO SR201 WEST BOUND & DROVER ANOTHER MILE WHE HE NOTICED FLUID POURING OUT OF THE REAR OF HIS TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD & RADIOED THE CITY DISPTACHER FOR HELP.  THE CITY DISPATCHER CALLED EMERGENCY 911 TO SUMMON POLICE TO THE SCENE.  SHIPPER USED A PLASTIC BLADDER TO CONTAIN FLUID. THEY USUALLY USE A "RUBBER" BLADDER PER OUR P&D DRIVER.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT ZERWECK WAS NOTIFIED BY REGIONAL MANAGER ROBINSON AT 0030 OF DERAILMENT INVOLVING TRAIN LIFW 13 AT SHREVEPORT.  CAR UNPX 120680 WAS INVOLVED AND THE CONTENTS WERE ON FIRE.  ON ARRIVAL ZERWECK MET WITH ED BOBBITT, LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAZMAT, AND DETERMINED THE CONTENTS TO BE SODIUM CHLORATE ON FIRE IN THE BALLAST.  ZERWECK, BOBBITT, AND THREE CADDO COUNTY FIRE FIGHTERS USED A 2 1/2 INCH WATER LINE TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE BY 0700.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT FROM RIPS TO THE CAR WAS ESTIMATED AT 400 LBS.  TERRY LITCHFIELD, CXY CHEMICAL WAS ON THE SCENE BY 0830 AS WAS TOM ROBINSON WILL SUPPLEMENT THIS REPORT DETAILING THE CLEANUP. SUPPLEMENTAL INFORMATION AS REPORTED BY T.M. ROBINSON, SR., REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD:  HOPPER CA UPNX 120860, A LOAD OF SODIUM CHLORATE IN CRYSTALLINE FORM, IS OF ALLUMINUM CONSTRUCTION.  AS A RESULT OF THE DERAILMENT, THE CAR SUSTAINED DAMAGE WHICH RESULTED IN LOSS OF AN ESTIMATED 2 TO 3 PERCENT OF THE LOAD. THIS INCLUDES PRODUCT LOST DURING THE SUBSEQUENT TRANSFER OPERATION. DAMAGE TO THE CAR CONSISTED OF "CUTS" ALONG THE SIDES AND THE DROP BINS OF EACH HOPPER.  THE INITIAL LOSS OF CONTENTS DUE TO THESE CUTS WAS APPROXIMATELY 400 POUNDS.  RESOURCES UTILIZED BY UPRR TO CONTROL AND MITIGATE THIS INCIDENT INCLUDED EMTECH INC. AND RONNIE WALL INC.  DURING THE FIRST DISCUSSIONS REGARDING REMOVAL OF THE HOPPER CAR FROM THE RAILROAD RIGHT OF WAY, CONCERN WAS VOICED THAT A LARGE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WOULD BE SPILLED AND LOST.  IT WAS FEARED THAT THIS WOULD CREATE A MORE HAZARDOUS SITUATION.  MECHANICAL METHODS OF PRODUCT REMOVAL WERE DISCUSSED, (VACUMN TRUCK, AUGER CONVEYER), HOWEVER THE SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES OBJECTED.  THEY WERE CONCERNED THAT THIS MIGHT RESULT IN FIRE EXPLOSION.  AFTER WEIGHING NUMEROUS OPTIONS, CONCENSUS WAS REACHED TO MOVE THE CAR FROM THE R.O.W.  THE MAINLINE RAIL IMMEDIATELY ADJACENT TO THE HOPPER CAR WAS REMOVED.  THE CAR WAS CLOAKED IN PLASTIC SHEETING AND THE GROUND WAS COVERED WITH PLASTIC SHEETING.  THEN THE R.O.W.  THIS WAS COMPLETED WITH ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT OF ADDITIONAL PRODUCT SPILLING. EMTECH AND RONNIE WALL PERSONNEL REMOVED THE SPILLED PRODUCT FROM THE R.O.W. THAT COULD BE SALVAGED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT THEN DISSOLVED THE REMAINDER TO ELIMINATE THE HAZARDS.  UPPR M.O.W. FORCES RESTORED THE TRACK TO SERVICE AT ABOUT 2359 HOURSOF 9/14/95.  UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF UPRR-CTSG AND CXYCHEM, EMTECH AND RONNIE WALL TRANSFERRED THE REMAINING CHLORATE FROM THE DAMAGED CAR.  ON FRIDAY AFTER (9/15/95), UPRR-CTSG MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO CONTINUE  MANAGEMENT OF THE MITIGATION PROJECT FOR UPRR. THIS WORK CONTINUED THROUGH SUNDAY, 9/17/95.  THE RECOVERED SODIUM CHLORATE WAS TRUCKED TO CXYCHEM'S TERMINAL AT SOUTH TEXARKANA, TX.

WHITELEY, PORTLAND OR., WAS NOTIFIED BY TELEPHONE BY MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS TERRY MILLER, HINKLE YARD, HINKLE,OR., THAT CONTAINER TRLU 400848, HYDROCHLORIC ACID, MOVING ON TOP OF CONTAINER SEAU 475002, LAZY BOY FURNITURE, BOTH CONTAINERS MOVING PLATFORM DTTX  456152, SPOTTED WEST END BOWL TRACK NUMBER 45, HINKLE YARD, WAS ON FIRE.  HE ADVISED MYO MILLER THAT THERE WAS LIKELY A RELEASE OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID AND VISIBLE VAPORS WAS RESULT OF REACTION OF ACID WITH MATERIALS IT WAS COMING IN CONTACT WITH.  MYO MILLER HAD INITIATED EVACUATION OF HINKLE ONE-SPOT, DEPARTURE YARD, AND EAST END TRIM BUILDINGS, DUE TO DIRECTION OF PREVAILING WINDS.  HE ASKED MYO MILLER TO CALL EMERGENCY NUMBER ON SHIPPING PAPERS, CALL LOCAL 911 EMERGENCY NUMBER ON SHIPPING PAPERS, CALL 911 EMERGENCY NUMBER,AND ATTEMPT TO LOCATE OPERATOR OF HINKLE INTERMODAL PIGGY PACKER IN EVENT CONTAINER HAD TO BE GROUNDED.  HE CALLED OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, PORTLAND, OR., REQUESTED IMMEDIATE RESPONSE TO SCENE.  HE ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 0435 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 17, NOTING REAR DOORS OF CONTAINER HAD BEEN OPENED BY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PERSONNEL ON SCENE FROM HERMISTON FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE CONTAINER HAD NOT BEEN ENTERED AND VISIBLE VAPOR EMISSIONS WERE ALMOST ZERO.  ENTRY WAS MADE AND NOTED SIXTY(60) FIFTY-FIVE (55) GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS HAD SHIFTED FORWARD TOWARDS NOSE OF CONTAINER RESULTING IN VISIBLE CRUSHING AND RELEASE OF CONTENTS FROM FOUR (4)  PLASTIC DRUMS NEAR FRONT OF CONTAINER.  DUE TO CONDITIONS, I.E., DIMINISHED VAPOR RELEASE, SHIFTED CONDITION, AND NEED TO GROUND CONTAINER TO PROCEED, THE SCENE WAS RELEASED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO THE RAILROAD FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  STACK CAR DTTX 456152 AND COVERED HOPPER ITLX 40361, SODA ASH, WERE HANDLED WITH 10 BUFFER CARS TO ISOLATED LOCATION ON THE GRAVEL SPUR WEST OF THE YARD.  THE COVERED HOPPER CAR DISPLAYED EVIDENCE OF CONTAMINATION ON THE B OR WEST END.  THE CONTAINER WERE GROUNDED AND FIFTY-SIX(56) INTACT DRUMS OF ACID WERE REMOVED, DECONTAMINATED, RE-BANDED TO PALLETS, AND LOADED INTO TRAILER INBU 499647. THE FOUR (4) CRUSHED DRUMS AND RESIDUE WERE OVERPACKED AND ARE AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE DISPOSITION OF FURNITURE MOVING IN SEAU 475002 IS PENDING.  THE DISPOSITION OF FURNITURE MOVING IN SEAU 475002 IS PENDING.  DTTX 456152 WITH CONTAINER TRLU 400848 (PLACARDED CORROSIVE), AND CONTAINER SEAU 475002, WAS HANDLED FROM HINKLE SET OUT RACK WITH MOTIVE POWER AT APPROXIMATELY 0050 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 17, 1995, TO BOWL TRACK NUMBER 45 WHERE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO ROLL FREE BY CREW OF JOB HK 32, FOREMAN GENE HULL, ENGINEER ANDY BAKER, SWITCHMAN V.M. PIERCEY. SUBSEQUENT IMPACT WITH WEST CAR ITLX 40361, SODA ASH, AND OTHER STANDING CARS IN TRACK RESULTED IN THE LOAD SHIFT AND RELEASE OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID. THE VAPOR CLOUD FROM THIS CAR WAS INITIALLY OBSERBED BY TOWER YARDMASTER WHO PROMPTLY NOTIFIED MYO MILLER OF SITUATION.  DETA

column168: OUR DRIVER HAD FINISHED LOADING AT THE LOADING RACK AND PROCEEDED TO MOVE HIS VEHICLE.  THE DRIVER HAD NOT PROPERLY DISCONNECTED FROM THE RACK CAUSING DAMAGE TO THE RACK AND A LOSS OF THE MATERIAL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE SHIPPERS CONTAINMENT BASIN AND DISPOSED OF BY THE SHIPPER.
THE CAP CAME OFF OF THE CONTAINER ON THE TOP BELT OF PD4 DUMPING 2 1/2 GALLONS ON THE BELT CAUSING 30 REBOXES.
RESPONDED TO SPILL AND USED DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET, (PH OF 11).  NEUTRALIZED SPILL WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND PROCESSED THROUGH DMP FOR PROPER PROPOSAL.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: A R.L. VALLEE DRIVER, SCOTT ANDERSON, OVERTURNED A GASOLINE TANKER TRUCK ON SOUTH SIDE OF ROUTE 104A ON SEPTEMBER 1, 1995.  APPROXIMATELY 4616 GALLONS GASOLINE WERE LOST INTO SURFACE AND SUBSURFACE SOILS AT THE SITE. MR. ANDERSON HAD BEEN ON DUTY APPROXIMATELY 2 HOURS.  ROAD CONDITIONS WERE EXCELLENT, WEATHER WAS CLEAR AND SUNNY.  ANDER WAS TRAVELING EAST ON 104A, AND ROLLED THE UNIT ON A SHARP CURVE.  EQUIPMENT CONDITION WAS EXCELLENT: TRACTOR 8,000 MILES AND TRAILER 3-4 YEARS OLD.  PLEASE NOTE THE DRIVER/R.L. VALEE OFFICE DID EXCELLENT JOB NOTIFYING ALL EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCIES.  CAUSE OF ACCIDENT:  DRIVER TRAVELING TOO FAST FOR ROAD CONDITIONS.  ACTION TAKEN:  MR. ANDERSON WAS TERMINATED.  FUTURE COURSE: EMPLOYEE MATURE DRIVER WITH 5 TO 10 YEARS DRIVING EXPERIENCE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis
